  "datePublished": "2026-03-31",
  "description": "Gravitational lensing is the bending of light by massive objects, predicted by general relativity. When light from a distant source passes near a massive foreground object (a galaxy, galaxy cluster, or other concentration of mass), the curvature of spacetime deflects the light\u0026rsquo;s path, distorting, magnifying, or multiplying the image of the background source.\nThree regimes are distinguished:\nStrong lensing. The foreground mass is dense enough to produce multiple images, arcs, or complete rings (Einstein rings) of the background source. Galaxy clusters frequently produce strong lensing.\n",
